(366, 1, '2012-08-04 17:25:49', '2012-08-04 21:25:49', 'Maragatham Ramaswamy is a seasoned and well known musician who has been performing and training disciples in the DC metro area in the tradition of Carnatic Music.\r\n\r\nMaragatham was formally educated and trained as a vocalist and a violinist. Earning the title of <em>Sangeetha Vidhwan</em> at an early age in these two pursuits, she has performed at prestigious <em>sabhas</em> in Madras and at All India Radio, Madras before she moved to the United States in the 1980s with her family. When she first arrived in the US, Maragatham was approached by many interested students (and parents) interested in learning Carnatic music. She set up the music school, “Ragamalika” in 1987. Ragamalika reflects her unique methods of training that result in outstanding, coordinated and sweet musical performances by her students. This year Ragamalika is celebrating its 25<sup>th</sup> year of existence.\r\n\r\nMaragatham started training as a violinist under Sri. Trivandrum Harihar Iyer at an early age. Later she honed her violin skills under maestros Lalgudi Jayaraman, M.S. Anantharaman and T.N. Krishnan. As a vocalist, she trained under the renowned Sri S. Kalayanaraman, who himself was the disciple of the maestro G.N. Balasubramaniam. She has also trained under prominent musicians such as Palghat K.V.Narayanaswamy, T.M.Thiagarajan, and Ramnad Krishnan.\r\n\r\nMaragatham graduated from the prestigious Music College of Madras with a Gold Medal for outstanding achievement. She has received many awards from prestigious organizations such as the Music Academy and the Krishna Gana Sabha for her vocal and violin performances. Prominent music critics in major Indian newspapers have recognized Maragatham for her "precise grasp of <em>laya</em> (rhythm) and exquisite sense of <em>raga</em>". (Indian Express)\r\n\r\nMaragatham auditioned and was accepted as an All India Radio artiste for violin and vocal performances, at All India Radio, Madras. She is the recipient of many awards. She was also honored by "Tamil Thenral Radio" for her outstanding contribution and achievement to Carnatic Music in the Washington D.C. Metropolitan area. She received the “Best Music Teacher” award from the Sivan Fine Arts Academy in Chennai. She also received an award from Vishwayogi Vishwamji Foundation award for her contribution to propagating Carnatic music in the West.\r\n\r\nIn addition to her Indian audiences, Maragatham has also been very active in the DC Area serving as an artiste, mentor, a teacher as well as a music consultant for public stage performances to American audiences. She was a music consultant for Terrence McNally''s "A Perfect Ganesh" performed at the Arena Stage in Washington D.C. She has performed at several venues in the Washington DC Metropolitan Area such as the "Asian Pacific American heritage Month", the Arthur M. Sackler Gallery, Festival of American Folk life: "Sacred Sounds” and the 20th and 21st Takoma Park festivals. She was featured in Washington Post Online.\r\n\r\nThrough the last 25 years, Maragatham continues to mold aspiring musicians young and old, through her school. She has developed a reputation of being a demanding yet compassionate and caring teacher. Her attention to detail and emphasis on rigor and discipline is self-evident in the high quality of her students’ performances.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Maragatham Ramaswamy', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'maragatham-ramaswamy', '', '', '2012-08-04 17:25:49', '2012-08-04 21:25:49', '', 0, 'http://bramkaslp01/ragamalika/?page_id=366', 0, 'page', '', 0),
